    INTRODUCTION
   
   
   The United States is engaged in a partnershipwith Ukraine to provide
   support during a crucial and difficult period ofeconomic and political
   transition. The success of this transitionrequires Ukrainian
   leadership to bring about profound change across thespectrum of
   Ukrainian institutions while dealing with the direconsequences of a
   failed system. Because it is in the U.S. interest that Ukraine become a
   secure and viable independent state able to participate fully in the
   world economy, the U.S. has offered to engage American expertise in
   building a market-oriented democracy.
   
   
   Based on a shared vision of what must be achieved to secure Ukraine's
   future, the objectives of U.S. assistance are to:
   
   * Foster the emergence of acompetitive, market-oriented economy in
   which the majority of economicresources are privately owned and
   managed;
   
   * Support the transition to democratic political systems,
   transparentand accountable governance and the empowerment of
   indigenous civic andeconomic organizations that ensure broad-based
   participation in economicand political life; and
   
   
   * StrengthenUkraine's capacity to manage the human dimension of the
   transition todemocracy and a market economy, and help sustain the
   neediest sectors ofthe population during the transition.
   
   
   Toensure maximum impact with limited resources, U.S. technical
   assistanceis carefully targeted to a number of key areas. These
   include:
   
   
   
   * Private Sector Development. To helpUkraine achieve a viable,
   market-oriented economy, U.S assistancesupports: the equitable and
   speedy privatization of small, medium andlarge enterprises;
   legislation and market structures and approaches tocreate private land
   and housing markets; investment in new businessesthrough an enterprise
   fund and technical assistance to emerging privatebusinesses in areas
   such as marketing, accounting and management; thedevelopment of
   capital markets; partnerships between American andUkrainian
   agribusiness interests to help create efficient food systems;local
   government provision of public services through private vendors;and
   education of Ukrainians about these initiatives and their impact.
   
   
   
   
   
   * Economic Restructuringand Financial Sector Reform. To aid Ukraine in
   making thetransition from a command economy to a market-based system
   and creatingan enabling environment in which business can flourish,
   the U.S.provides assistance to: improve fiscal management with new,
   modernfinancing and accountability mechanisms; implement sound
   monetary policyand modern banking methods; and strengthen and
   streamline the traderegime, including improvement of the customs
   system and assistance withthe process leading to accession to the
   General Agreement on Trade andTariffs (GATT).
   
   
   
   * Energy andEnvironment. To increase energy efficiency and
   reliability, improvedomestic fuel resources and nuclear safety, and
   foster a cleaner, saferenvironment, U.S assistance is: supporting the
   restructuring of thepower sector, including the development of a
   legal, regulatory andtariff framework and the corporatization of
   thermal power generationcompanies; introducing low-cost technology
   investments to a Kiev powerplant; identifying potential efficiency
   improvements and investmentneeds in industry, buildings and
   residences; assisting pilot initiativesthat could lead to improved
   utilization of domestic energy resources;working to improve the
   operations and safety of nuclear power plants;helping Ukraine to
   restructure its environmental management to meet theneeds of a market
   democracy, including pilot technology demonstrationprojects in the
   Donetsk region and concerning water resource management,strengthening
   non-governmental organization (NGO) public information
   andparticipation programs, and improving environmental information
   fordecision making.
   
   
   
   * DemocraticInitiatives. To foster the development of a democratic
   society withbroad-based participation in political and economic life,
   U.S.assistance is geared toward helping to increase public
   participation inthe political process, particularly by assisting
   political and governingindividuals to be more efficient, responsive
   and accountable; helping todevelop the appropriate legal framework
   that a market-oriented democracyneeds to function; and strengthening
   the capacity of Ukrainian NGOs. Complementary to these goals are U.S.
   training programs targeting highschool, undergraduate and gradate
   students, teachers and faculty,government officials, entrepreneurs and
   other professionals.
   
   
   
   * Social Support. To assist Ukraine inaddressing the deterioration of
   support systems such as health care,housing and municipal services
   caused by the breakdown of the Sovietsystem, and to help maintain the
   neediest sectors during the transition,the U.S. is: working with
   national, regional and local governments toredefine expenditure
   responsibilities and revenue options to financesocial and other public
   services; emphasizing improved social servicedelivery systems;
   supporting the efforts of NGOs to create a privatenetwork of social
   services; and providing short-term, critically neededhumanitarian
   assistance, such as vaccines and pharmaceuticals.
   
   
   
   
   
   In addition to technicalassistance, the United States has also
   provided humanitarian assistanceto Ukraine, specifically, critical
   vaccines and pharmaceuticals, as wellas food assistance. The U.S.
   assistance package to Ukraine alsoincludes USDA export credt
   guarantees, as well as investment insuranceand financing through the
   Overseas Private Investment Corporation(OPIC). Finally, the United
   States and Ukraine have agreed on a numberof cooperative threat
   reduction activities, such as nuclear armsdismantlement, which are
   being implemented with U.S. assistance underthe Nunn-Lugar program.
   
   
   
   The amount ofU.S. assistance to Ukraine is detailed in the table
   following thisintroduction. Since FY 1992 when the assistance program
   was initiated,a total of $853.4 million in total assistance has been
   obligated. Ofthat total assistance, $659.3 million has been obligated
   for economicassistance and $154.1 million in Nunn-Lugar monies.
   Included in theeconomic assistance package is a total of $510.6
   million in grants anddonations and $188.7 million in credits and
   insurance. A total of$339.1 million has been expended in both economic
   assistance andNunn-Lugar monies, including $265.8 million in grants
   and donations and$53.7 million in credits and insurance. U.S. support
   for Ukraine underIMF programs in FY 95 totals $350 million, comprising
   $148.5 million ingrants and donations and $201.5 million in credits
   and insurance. (Seecharts).
   
   
   
   Included in these levels arethe commitments made by President Clinton
   to Presidents Kravchuk andKuchma during their respective visits in
   1994. In March 1994, PresidentClinton pledged $700 million in
   assistance for Ukraine: $350 million toencourage and support major
   economic reform, to be provided in fivecategories of technical
   assistance, as well as medical and foodassistance and credit programs,
   and $350 million to implement theNunn-Lugar program. Of the $350
   million economic assistance, $266.6million has been obligated and
   $137.2 million expended through FY 1994. Of the $350 million
   Nunn-Lugar program, $154.1 million has beenobligated through FY 1994
   and $19.6 million has been expended. (Seefirst chart).
   
   
   
   In November 1994,President Clinton pledged an additional $200 million
   to Ukraine ineconomic assistance as part of a multilateral effort to
   supportUkraine's Systemic Transformation Facility agreement with the
   IMF, aswell as in response to Ukraine's approval of the
   Non-ProliferationTreaty. $100 million of this assistance is being
   provided asbalance-of-payments support in the form of an energy sector
   grant,credit and insurance programs, and additional technical
   assistancecommodities. (See second chart). The remaining $100 million
   will fundtechnical assistance in the areas outlined above. (See first
   chart). The energy sector grant was obligated and expended by 31
   December 1994.
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   In April 1995, the United States pledged support of $250 million
   toUkraine to support Ukraine's stand-by arrangement with the IMF
   andprovide balance-of-payments support. $175 million of this pledge
   willbe provided through the Ukraine Export Credit Insurance Program.
   $15million will come from technical assistance commodities with
   theremaining $60 million from medical and food donations. (See
   secondchart).
   
   
   
   The following report providesa comprehensive review of U.S.-funded
   assistance for Ukraine as of April1995.
   
   
   
   
   
    TECHNICALASSISTANCE PROGRAMS
   
   
   
   Ofthe $900 million pledged for Ukraine over the 1994-95 period,
   technicalassistance comprises $366.5 million: $195 million from the FY
   94 pledgeand $171.5 million from the FY 95 pledge, including the $72
   millionenergy sector grant. The majority of these programs are
   administered byUSAID, but other U.S. Government agencies, such as the
   United StatesInformation Agency (USIA) and the Trade and Development
   Agency (TDA),also contribute to the effort.
   
   
   
   Followingare descriptions of the five technical assistance programs
   offered toUkraine.
   
   I. PRIVATE SECTORDEVELOPMENT March 94 Pledge: $95.0 million
   
    FY94 Obligated: 78.3 million
   
    FY 95 Planned: 22.7 million
   
   
   
   A. Privatization:
   
   
   
   The U.S. program aims to accomplish thefollowing:
   
   
   
   * Support thedevelopment of market reform initiatives that are
   transparent, fair andspeedy, and that will enable all citizens to have
   the right to own andsell property and use these assets as collateral
   for business expansion,purchasing homes and restructuring existing
   enterprises.
   
   
   
   * Initiate Ukraine's mass privatizationprogram in 1995, transferring
   at least 8,000 medium and largeenterprises to the private sector. This
   program will be the drivingforce behind market reform.
   
   
   
   *Complete privatization of substantially all small-scale enterprisesby
   the end of 1995.
   
   
   
   * Promotethe development of capital markets, bringing necessary
   capital to bearto enable private sector-led enterprise and economic
   restructuring.
   
   *
   
   * Conduct a publiceducation campaign to inform Ukrainian citizens
   about privatization andmarket reform initiatives.
   
   
   
   Todate, the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * A framework for mass privatization has been jointlydeveloped and
   signed with the Ukrainian Government and other donors.
   
   
   
   * Close to eight million massprivatization certificates have been
   printed and delivered to Ukrainefor distribution to five pilot oblasts
   (regions). The balance ofcertificates will be sent to Ukraine in late
   December 1994, for a totalof about 50 million certificates.
   
   
   
   *Technical advice has been provided to a Cabinet of MinistersWorking
   Group for the development of a capital market framework.
   
   
   
   * USAID sponsored a public educationprogram in Kiev to train
   journalists, develop press clubs, providetelevision, radio and print
   advertising on mass privatization and marketreform.
   
   
   
   * Twenty-fiveparliamentarians and Government officials were sent to
   Prague and Moscowto review implementation of privatization and voucher
   privatization.
   
   
   
   * A group of policy-makers were sentto Russia to review the
   Anglo-western model of securities marketdevelopment.
   
   
   
   * A model forprivatizing bus routes (intra-city, suburban and
   intercity) wasdeveloped and implemented. As of September 1994, a total
   of 36 privatebus routes were operating in 11 cities, with an average
   of 84 busesrunning on these routes.
   
   
   
   Thefollowing assistance is continuing or new:
   
   
   
   * Technical assistance on contracting out public services toprivate
   vendors will be provided to municipalities and oblasts.
   
   
   
   * Assistance to expand private busroutes throughout Ukraine and to
   ensure the commercial viability ofprivate bus operations will be
   continued.
   
   
   
   * Through assistance from the International FinanceCorporation (IFC),
   the privatization of small enterprises bymunicipalities and oblasts
   will be accelerated.
   
   
   
   * Public education programs on privatization, corporategovernance and
   general market reform issues will continue to besupported.
   
   
   
   * Bid collectionand processing infrastructure and methodology will be
   established.
   
   
   
   * Pilot support activities withinvestment funds will be conducted and
   the development of aself-regulating association of investment funds
   and trust companies willbe supported.
   
   
   
   * Anindependent monitoring unit to track and report on developments
   withrespect to investment operations and share registry/transfer will
   beestablished.
   
   
   
   B. New BusinessDevelopment and Support for Investment:
   
   
   
   The U.S. program aims to accomplish the following:
   
   
   
   * Improve conditions conducive to privatebusiness development and
   investment and support the emergence of privatebusiness structures
   which can operate successfully in a competitivedomestic and
   international market environment.
   
   
   
   To date the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * The Eurasia Foundation has awardedapproximately 50 grants in Ukraine
   for over $1.5 million with a strongfocus on small business
   development.
   
   
   
   *The U.S. Trade and Development Agency (TDA) has awarded $1.7million
   to fund five feasibility studies by U.S. companies interested
   ininvesting in Ukraine.
   
   
   
   * Over200 American volunteers have provided assistance under
   theFarmer-to-Farmer program.
   
   
   
   * Pilottraining and technical assistance in marketing was provided to
   UkraineInternational Airlines to strengthen its professional
   capability to be acompetitive international airline.
   
   
   
   *A USAID grant was made to CDV Apple Computer Inc. and
   RennsaelerPolytechnique Institute to support their program:
   "Initiative forUkraine", which is training master trainers to develop
   industry skillsin designing and marketing commercially successful
   computer software forinternational markets.
   
   
   
   The followingassistance is continuing or new:
   
   
   
   *USAID will begin implementation in early 1995 of a $12.5
   millionbusiness development project providing for institutional
   development ofbusiness support centers and mass production and
   dissemination oftraining materials for new business start-up and
   operation.
   
   
   
   * The $150 million Western NISEnterprise Fund, announced by the White
   House in July 1994, will openits official Ukraine office early in 1995
   and plans to initiate itsoperations with the opening of a small loan
   window to support smallbusiness development. Opportunities already
   submitted to the Fund forinvestment and lending are being assessed by
   the New York Office.
   
   
   
   * 103 Peace Corps volunteers areproviding advisory services to
   emerging businesses in 35 cities acrossUkraine.
   
   
   
   * TheUSAID-funded American Business Center, managed by the Foreign
   CommercialService of the U.S. Department of Commerce, will open in
   Kiev in spring1995 to serve as a hub for contacts between American and
   Ukrainianbusinesses.
   
   
   
   
   
   *TDA continues to provide support for feasibilities studies relatedto
   major projects. Two feasibility study proposals worth $700 thousandare
   currently under consideration. They are focused on nuclear
   safety,development of a new banking network using "smart cards",
   andmodernization of the Kharkiv Airport.
   
   
   
   *Five U.S. firms are involved in agribusiness partnerships --
   AvianFarms, Cargill Enterprises, Freedom Farms International, Monsanto
   andKiev-Atlantic -- with a number of benefits already evident.
   Forexample, Monsanto's partnership with Beshevsky has led the
   oblastgovernment to take the lead in enlarging this input supply
   operation toinclude all the farms in the area. Also, Freedom Farms
   International'swork has resulted in an improvement in crop mix for
   bettermerchandising.
   
   
   
   * In1994, the U.S. Department of Agriculture provided for a two-year
   periodan advisor to the Minister of Agriculture to formulate policy
   optionsfor the reform of the agriculture sector, bringing to bear
   relevantinformation and experience of leading agriculture experts
   andinstitutions from the United States.
   
   
   
   Thefollowing concerns jeopardize progress in this program:
   
   
   
   * Without changes in tax laws and administration, thereis limited
   opportunity for development of a strong and stable domesticprivate
   business sector. The current tax laws represent a heavy burden,change
   frequently, and are confusing, contradictory and inconsistent intheir
   administration. They offer few incentives for the development ofsmall
   and medium-size businesses and there is high incidence of tax andother
   regulatory avoidance.
   
   
   
   *The share of the West NIS Enterprise Fund's capital invested in anyof
   the three western NIS countries will depend on the nature of
   thebusiness environment and opportunities for profitable ventures.
   Tosecure investments by the Fund, the challenge for Ukraine is to
   createand sustain an environment for viable business opportunities.
   
   
   
   * The difficult business environment isalso affecting U.S.
   agribusiness partners' operations. Specificconcerns include foreign
   exchange surrender requirements, export duties,price margin
   restrictions, continued use of "state order" systems,export licenses,
   contract compliance and lack of contract law.
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   C. Land and Real Estate Reformand Private Ownership of Property
   
   
   
   TheU.S. program aims to accomplish the following:
   
   
   
   * Encourage an accelerated pace of land privatization andprivate
   ownership as part of Ukraine's overall transition to a marketoriented
   economy in agricultural and urban areas while protecting theinterests
   of citizens during the transitional period.
   
   
   
   * Establish a comprehensive right to housing as privateproperty and
   facilitate an increased pace of privatization of thegovernment-owned
   (State and municipal) housing stock of both units andbuildings,
   including mixed commercial/residential buildings.
   
   
   
   * Establish a national core of Ukrainianexperts that can manage,
   expand nationally and deepen the reformapproaches developed and tested
   with USAID assistance.
   
   
   
   To date, the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * A senior land privatization advisorand USAID experts have assisted a
   government working commission toprepare a new national code on land,
   as well as new laws addressingenterprise land, titling and
   registration of property interests andterritorial planning, which will
   establish a comprehensive right toprivate property in land.
   
   
   
   * Themethodology and legal documentation for holding open, competitive
   landauctions, selling land outright where permitted or otherwise
   long-termleases to physical and juridical persons for objects of
   marketinfrastructure and housing has been developed and
   successfullyimplemented. The third Kharkiv land auction was held
   successfully inOctober 1994 with a fourth planned for January 1995.
   Lviv successfullyheld its first land auction in December 1994, to be
   followed by Odessaand Chernihiv later that month.
   
   
   
   * In September 1994, agroup of 21 delegates from the Supreme Rada,
   accompanied by Cabinetofficials, went to the U.S. on a study tour on
   private land and realestate markets in preparation for their review of
   the new package ofland legislation expected to come before the Rada in
   early 1995.
   
   
   
   * With USAID assistance, the City ofChernihiv has developed a zoning
   approach to land use planning andcontrol which creates flexibility for
   market-determined uses, speedsapproval processes and broadens choices
   for private investors whileprotecting the interests of society.
   
   
   
   
   
   * National conferences on Land Reform (April 1994) andon National
   Housing Policy (December 1994) were jointly sponsored withthe
   Government of Ukraine to establish the agenda of working
   commissionsdeveloping national legislation.
   
   
   
   *A national law for joint-private ownership of residential buildingsby
   Associations of Homeowners (condominium ownership) has been
   preparedjointly with the government.
   
   
   
   *Residents of seven buildings in Kharkiv are preparing
   legaldocumentation including model resolution, by-laws and
   ownershipdocuments and have undergone training in preparation to
   convert to fulloperational private condominium ownership. City action
   on the officialresolution is expected in December 1994.
   
   
   
   * Twenty-five government housing management and maintenanceofficials
   and some private entrepreneurs undertook a study tour to theU.S. to
   study approaches to housing management and maintenance invarious types
   of privately-owned and publicly-owned housing.
   
   
   
   The following assistance is continuing or new:
   
   
   
   * In August 1994, a senior housingpolicy advisor began to work with a
   national working commission toproduce a new national housing code and
   related legislation.
   
   
   
   * Project feasibility studies will beundertaken in three cities
   preparatory to and in conjunction with aproposed $40-50 million World
   Bank Housing Sector Loan. The loan willfocus on the establishment of
   the role of private developers inproduction of new and rehabilitated
   housing. USAID funds will be usedto leverage World Bank loan funds
   into Ukraine, which will dramaticallyincrease the positive impact in
   the housing sector.
   
   
   
   * A concept paper/workplan for thedevelopment of private sector
   housing finance options will be researchedand prepared jointly with
   the Government of Ukraine and the existingprivate sector, i.e., banks
   and investment funds such as the W/NISEnterprise Fund.
   
   
   
   * Ukrainianteams of experts have been mobilized to undertake training
   of trainersand information dissemination nationwide on approaches to
   land andhousing privatization and creation of related markets.
   
   
   
   * A simplified, cost effective,computer-aided approach to land use
   titling and registration of privateproperty will be tested in
   Vishgorod to establish a model for nationaluse.
   
   
   
   * A methodology anddemonstration project for sale and development of
   large urban parcelsthrough open, international competition using a
   request forproposals/tender approach will be tested in Odessa in early
   1995.
   
   
   
   * The creation of the UkrainianAssociation of Realtors and the
   Ukrainian Association of Appraisers hasbeen assisted and continues to
   be supported.
   
   
   
   * Media capability to report and educate on issues ofprivate land and
   housing markets will be developed.
   
   
   
   The following concern jeopardizes progress in this program:
   
   
   
   * To move to fully operational privateland and real estate markets,
   the Ukrainian Government needs to act ondraft legislation to broaden
   private ownership and allow the sale andmortgage of land and real
   estate.
   
   
   
   II. ECONOMIC RESTRUCTURING
   
   AND BANKING PledgeMarch 94: $10.0 million
   
    Obligated FY 94: 10.0 million
   
    Planned FY 95: 5.0 million
   
   
   
   The U.S. program aims to accomplish thefollowing:
   
   
   
   * Encourageinitiatives and provide advice that support comprehensive
   financial andfiscal reform, particularly at the macro-financial policy
   level, alsoaffecting intergovernmental fiscal relationships.
   
   
   
   * Strengthen Ukraine's new financial training institutefor commercial
   bankers and the staff of the National Bank of Ukraine. Provide
   hardware, software and technical assistance for the NationalBank's
   interbank payments system. Strengthen the functioning of thebank in
   such areas as bank supervision, accounting and other "backoffice"
   activities, economic policy and research.
   
   
   
   * Provide technical assistance for the process leadingto complete
   accession of Ukraine to GATT and assist in the harmonizationof
   Ukrainian laws with GATT principles and standards.
   
   
   
   * Assist in strengthening national systems and policiesthat produce a
   streamlined and effective trade regime, includingimprovement of the
   customs system.
   
   
   
   Todate, the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * Four study tours to the United States have beencompleted for
   approximately forty central and commercial bank personnelfocusing on
   such issues as bank supervision, risk management, monetaryand credit
   policy and economic research.
   
   
   
   * A procurement plan has been completed for the computerequipment
   necessary to help upgrade the payments system for the NationalBank of
   Ukraine. A January 1995 delivery is planned.
   
   
   
   * Long-term tax administration assistance at the StateTax Inspectorate
   is underway. Approximately 36 STI officials from thenational and
   regional levels have been trained in the United States, andtraining
   for about 24 more is planned. The Internal Revenue Service(IRS) and
   AED provide the training.
   
   
   
   
   
   * The Institute for Reform and the Informal Sector(IRIS) at the
   University of Maryland provided a trade regulation expertto the
   Ukrainian Antimonopoly Committee to draft an unfair competitionlaw.
   The expert assisted the committee in drafting a decree to specifythe
   minimum content of advertising of investment funds, which can serveas
   an interim step until a more thorough securities regulation regime
   isput in place.
   
   
   
   * A fiscalanalysis unit has been established at the Ministry of
   Finance under thejoint sponsorship of the Ministries of Finance,
   Economy and Statisticsand the Department of Customs. A workplan has
   been completed and hasreceived joint Ukrainian and USAID approval.
   
   
   
   * IRIS customs and international trade experts arrangedfor high-
   ranking Ukrainian Customs officials and a member of the Radawho
   oversees customs matters to visit the U.S. to see customsinstallations
   and to meet with U.S. customs and private experts.
   
   
   
   * Four commercial bankers havecompleted internships in U.S. banks.
   
   
   
   Thefollowing activities are continuing or new:
   
   
   
   * The National Center for Training of Bank Personnel, thefirst of its
   kind in the NIS, opened in January 1994 with a curriculumof nineteen
   advanced courses in commercial banking and specializedsubjects for the
   central bank. By the end of the year, professionaltraining will have
   been provided to nearly 900 bankers from more thanninety banks
   throughout Ukraine. Although training is centered in Kiev,courses have
   also been offered in several other cities across thecountry. In
   December 1994, the Center moved to a new facility providedby the
   National Bank of Ukraine, with training and equipment provided
   byUSAID. It is now fully registered and as insulated from
   politicalpressure as possible, and student tuitions have been exempted
   from thevalue-added tax.
   
   
   
   * Along-term advisor has begun working with the National Bank of
   Ukraine toestablish a policy analysis and research capability.
   
   
   
   * A long-term GATT advisor to the Ministry of ForeignEconomic
   Relations arrived in Kiev in October 1994 to provide day-to-dayadvice
   on GATT/WTO issues, including customs matters, trade in
   services,investment issues, intellectual property rights, standards,
   procurement,state trading, and other appropriate topics. The adviser
   also willprovide advice on what institutional and legal structures are
   bestsuited to ensuring that GATT/WTO obligations resulting from
   accessionare fully implemented at all levels of government.
   
   
   
   
   
   * A five-week training course wasrecently held for twelve Ukrainian
   GATT officials at the GATTsecretariat in Geneva. The long-term GATT
   adviser will help designfollow-on courses as necessary during the
   accession process.
   
   
   
   * The work of the GATT advisor will besupplemented by short-term
   experts to address specific topics of concernto the Government of
   Ukraine involving both accession to andimplementation of the GATT.
   
   
   
   *Two U.S. customs experts arrived in Kiev in September to work withthe
   State Customs Committee to develop training programs forpolicy-level
   customs officials.
   
   
   
   *A pilot project is underway in Lviv to train city engineers inmethods
   of raising capital, including loans from multilateral lenders.
   
   
   
   The following concerns jeopardize programprogress:
   
   
   
   * Unless thereform efforts begun at the macroeconomic level continue
   and some basicchanges are made in the policies and laws affecting
   banking, developmentof the financial sector will be slow and bankers'
   training will havelimited immediate impact on the effectiveness of
   financial institutionsin Ukraine.
   
   
   
   * Given theunstable macroeconomic environment, financial
   intermediaries still havelittle incentive to lend to the private
   sector because of riskconsiderations.
   
   
   
   * Establishmentof an inter-ministerial oversight group on tax policy
   will be necessaryto make effective use of USAID and IMF long-term
   advisors working on thedevelopment of a fiscal analysis unit.
   
   
   
   * Further training in municipal budgeting depends onidentification by
   Ukraine of appropriate oblasts for pilot projects andapproval of the
   scope of work.
   
   III. ENERGY ANDENVIRONMENT March 94 Pledge: $52.0 million
   
    FY 94 Obligated: 22.7 million
   
    FY95 Planned: $35.0 million
   
   
   
   A. PowerSector Restructuring and Energy Efficiency
   
   
   
   The U.S. program aims to accomplish the following:
   
   
   
   * Assist the restructuring of the power sector,including the
   development of a legal, regulatory and tariff frameworkand the
