   C. Investment Financing and Political Risk Insurance
   
   
   
   Overseas Private InvestmentCorporation (OPIC) Finance and Insurance
   Program
   
   
   
   OPIC provides political risk insurance coverage and some
   equityinvestment for American joint ventures in Ukraine.
   
   
   
   To date, the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * Since January 1994, OPIC committedinsurance totaling more than $30
   million to four projects inUkraine--Alliant Techsystems, Universal
   Research Technologies,Generation Ukraine, and Intertrade Uzviv L.L.C.
   
   
   
   * In addition, OPIC has committed approximately $200,000to two
   feasibility studies for U.S.-sponsored oil and agribusinessprojects in
   Ukraine.
   
   
   
   The followingactivities are continuing or new:
   
   
   
   *OPIC expects to approve approximately $25 million in insurance fortwo
   food distribution projects in Ukraine.
   
   
   
   * During President Kuchma's November 1994 visit, OPIC signeda protocol
   to provide finance and insurance support to FMC
   Corporation'sharvesting equipment leasing project in Ukraine.
   
   
   
   * Witnessed by President Clinton and President Kuchma,OPIC and Alliant
   Techsystems signed a protocol to provide financing toAlliant's
   investment in a defense conversion joint venture.
   
   
   
   * OPIC is working hard to encourageinvestment in Ukraine through
   investment development programs. Forexample, in August 1994, OPIC
   hosted an Investor Conference onAgribusinesses in Ukraine. OPIC
   brought 25 Ukrainian agribusinessrepresentatives to the U.S. for
   meetings in Washington D.C. and Iowa. The program was designed to
   stimulate the development of joint venturesbetween U.S. and Ukrainian
   companies which OPIC may be able to support. OPIC is continuing to
   follow up on potential projects.
   
   
   
   * In November 1994, OPIC hosted a senior executiveroundtable which
   afforded President Kuchma and his delegation theopportunity to discuss
   investment opportunities and commercialopportunities directly with the
   U.S. business community. Over 100 U.S.business and government
   officials attended this important event.
   
   
   
   The following concerns jeopardize programprogress:
   
   
   
   OPIC can encourage U.S.companies to make investments by ameliorating
   political and commercialrisks, but it cannot force U.S. companies to
   show an interest in aninvestment climate that is relatively
   unattractive due to a lack ofeconomic reform. Reforms crucial to
   American investment include:
   
   
   
   * Tight monetary policy to createconfidence in long-term reductions in
   inflation. U.S. companies arevery hesitant to invest in projects in
   Ukraine's volatile inflationaryenvironment. No company can make an
   accurate assessment of profitsbased on "koupon" revenues in the
   current situation;
   
   
   
   * Expansion of privatization/private land ownership. U.S. companies
   are very unlikely to invest in projects in which theycannot have true
   ownership or management control. Further, by law, OPICcannot support
   projects that do not have a significant amount of U.S.equity
   ownership;
   
   
   
   * Changein the regulations governing the repatriation of export
   revenues. Currently, firms in Ukraine that earn hard currency through
   exporttransactions must exchange repatriated revenues for "koupons" at
   anofficial rate much below the actual market rate. The
   regulationeffectively places a high tax on exporters.
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   COOPERATIVE THREATREDUCTION AND RELATED ASSISTANCE PROGRAMS
   
   
   
   
   
    March94 Pledge: $350 million 
   
