   On October 25, 1993, the foreign ministers of the United States
   andUkraine signed the Safe, Secure Dismantlement (SSD) Umbrella
   agreement. This agreement provides the legal framework for the
   provision ofNunn-Lugar assistance to Ukraine. In March 1994, the
   United Statesoffered to increase by $175 million its offer of
   assistance to Ukraine,bringing the total to $350 million in
   Nunn-Lugarassistance--approximately $275 million out of existing
   funding and $75million out of FY95 funding. Approximately $130 million
   has beenobligated for material, training, and services to Ukraine
   inimplementing assistance projects.
   
   
   
   TheCooperative Threat Reduction Assistance package is divided into
   severalcategories of assistance, including:
   
   
   
   
   
   A. STRATEGIC NUCLEAR ARMS DISMANTLEMENT Agreements: $185million
   
   
   
   This is the largestportion of the U.S. assistance package. Assistance
   in this area willhelp--and potentially accelerate--Ukraine's ability
   to meet itsobligations under the START Treaty and the Trilateral
   statement bydeactivating and eliminating ICBMs and ICBM silos deployed
   on Ukrainianterritory.
   
   
   
   To date, the followingassistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   *In 1994, the U.S. provided strategic nuclear arms
   eliminationequipment, including cranes, all-terrain vehicles,
   emergency accessequipment, communications equipment, truck batteries,
   power saws, 2000metric tons of gasoline and diesel fuel, and other
   tools and supplies. A substantial portion of the supplies (fuel,
   tires, batteries, etc.) waspurchased directly from the Ukrainian
   economy, creating an infusion ofhard currency.
   
   
   
   * In April,the U.S. awarded contracts to Ukrainian companies to design
   an SS-19neutralization facility, construct a missile storage
   yard--recentlycompleted--and build overhead bridge cranes for the
   neutralizationfacility at Dnipropetrovsk. Funding for this program
   will also help payfor temporary housing for workers involved in
   dismantling silos.
   
   
   
   * A large amount of silo dismantlementequipment--as well as emergency
   support equipment--to be delivered inDecember 1994.
   
   
   
   * InAugust/September, the U.S. agreed to provide heptyl storage
   containersfor Ukraine and
   
   signed a contract with aUkrainian firm to produce those containers.
   
   
   
   
   
   B. INDUSTRIALPARTNERSHIPS Agreements: $40 million
   
   
   
   In March 1994, the U.S. and Ukraine signed an agreement for up to
   $40million in defense conversion assistance. This funding will
   supportjoint business initiatives to convert selected defense
   industriesinvolved in weapons of mass destruction (WMD) production to
   civilianactivities, such as projects to produce prefabricated housing
   fordemobilized Strategic Rocket Forces servicemen.
   
   
   
   To date, the following assistance has been completed:
   
   
   
   * $5 million has been provided toWestinghouse Corporation--which
   contributed an additional $14million--to work with the Ukrainian
   company Hartron. The resultingjoint-venture, Westron, will produce
   electronic control technology thatcan improve the safety of nuclear
   reactors in Ukraine and elsewhere. Westron foresees projects earning
   $100 million in revenues.
   
   
   
   * The U.S. company Harbert International hasbeen awarded a $10 million
   grant to team with Fregat, a former defensecompany in Ukraine, to
   produce prefabricated housing for demobilized SRFpersonnel living near
   Pervomaysk.
   
   
   
   *Additional partnerships include ABB SUSA and American Services,
   Incwhich have been awarded $20 million to work with Ukrainian
   companiesthat formerly produced ICBM silos. This partnership will
   develop acivil engineering industrial partnership project that will
   producecivilian housing, including a housing complex for about 500
   demobilizedSRF personnel near Khmelnytskyy, employing hundreds of
   Ukrainians.
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   C. EXPORT CONTROL Agreements: $7.26 million
   
   
   
   The U.S. will provide training and equipment tohelp Ukraine upgrade
   its export control system as an aid to preventingthe proliferation of
   weapons of mass destruction and thus improvingUkrainian and
   international security.
   
   
   
   
   
   
   
   D. EMERGENCY RESPONSE EQUIPMENT Agreements: $5 million
   
   
   
   The U.S. willprovide emergency response training, clothing and
   equipment to improveUkraine's ability to respond in the event of an
   accident involving theremoval of a nuclear weapon or transport of
   ICBMs on its territory.
   
   
   
   
   
   E. GOVERNMENT TO GOVERNMENT 
   
   COMMUNICATIONS LINK Agreements: $2.4 million
   
   
   
   Assistance will be provided to help Ukraine establisha direct
   communications link with the U.S. for the transmission ofrequired
   notifications under the START and INF Treaties.
   
   
   
   * Interim terminal equipment for thegovernment to government
   communications link will be provided inOctober.
   
   
   
   
   
   F. MATERIAL CONTROL, ACCOUNTING, PROTECTION Agreements: $12.5 million
   
   
   
   U.S. assistance will help to establish a systemto help Ukraine account
   for and physically protect civilian nuclearmaterial on its territory,
   increasing nuclear safety and security inUkraine, as well as providing
   technology, equipment and training.
   
   
   
   
   
   G. DEFENSE AND MILITARYCONTACTS MOU: $3.9 million
   
   
   
   Byexpanding U.S.-Ukrainian defense and military contacts, this
   programpromotes transition and reform and builds strong working
   relationships. This plays an important role in our efforts to enhance
   Ukraine's overallsecurity and to assist with conventional force
   restructuring. Examplesof planned activities include:
   
   
   
   *Visits of Ukrainian officers to U.S. officer professionaldevelopment
   schools
   
   
   
   * Visitsof Ukrainian military personnel to the U.S. Army
   Non-CommissionedOfficer Training Center.
   
   
   
   * Thevisit of a U.S. Army delegation to a Ukrainian enlisted
   personnelcenter.
   
   
   
   * Regular JointStaff talks.
   
   
   
   * BiannualBilateral Working Group meetings.
   
   
   
   *Joint military exercises.
   
   
   
   
   
   H. SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGYCENTER Agreements: $10 million
   
   
   
   TheUnited States, Canada and Sweden will provide funding for the
   Scienceand Technology Center in Ukraine (STCU). The objective of the
   STCU isto give weapons scientists and engineers, particularly those
   withknowledge and skills related to weapons of mass destruction or
   missiledelivery systems, opportunities to redirect their talents to
   peacefulpurposes.
   
   
   
   
   
   I. NUCLEAR REACTOR SAFETY Agreements: $11 million
   
   
   
   As part of a broader Western effort to enhance thesafety of civilian
   nuclear power plants in Ukraine, the U.S. willconstruct a reactor
   simulator on which reactor operators will be trainedin the safe
   operation of such power plants. This will provide for saferreactors
   and nuclear energy use in Ukraine for the future.
